WEBVTT

0:00:00.000 --> 0:00:08.032
Open a file

0:00:08.032 --> 0:00:13.031
As this is a compressed file, Chirpity will extract it.

0:00:15.031 --> 0:00:18.030
Once extracted, the spectrogram is created.

0:00:19.030 --> 0:00:22.629
Exploring the transport controls, we can see the file name, play / pause, spectrogram zoom and filter panel

0:00:22.629 --> 0:00:29.628
The filter panel allows you to turn on Nocmig mode, which limits file analysis to night time periods

0:00:30.628 --> 0:00:40.626
Let's analyse the file.

0:00:46.625 --> 0:00:50.624
When complete, any detections made appear below the spectrogram. Chirpity will jump to the location of the first detection and highlight it.

0:00:50.624 --> 0:00:52.624
A right-click on the highlighted area opens a context menu.

0:00:52.624 --> 0:00:54.624
Let's play this clip

0:00:58.622 --> 0:01:01.015
Selecting another species that's been detected will instantly move you to that detection in the file

0:01:08.587 --> 0:01:15.019
Click the expand icon at the top right of the spectrogram to enter fullscreen mode

0:01:17.685 --> 0:01:20.685
Plus and minus keys zoom the spectrogram

0:01:21.018 --> 0:01:24.517
Hold shift while pressing plus or minus to change the FFT window

0:01:27.283 --> 0:01:30.283
Return to results view by pressing the fullscreen icon again

0:01:32.649 --> 0:01:37.648
Another context menu option allows you to analyse just the highlighted portion of audio

0:01:47.279 --> 0:01:51.278
You can also save the record to the archive database from here.

0:01:53.278 --> 0:01:58.010
In the popup, you can tag the record, change the ID, add a call count and any comments you want to add.

0:02:01.776 --> 0:02:04.776
A confirmation will appear...

0:02:11.608 --> 0:02:14.607
You can use the filter panel to apply audio filters and reduce background noise.

0:02:24.672 --> 0:02:35.003
These filters can be used to fine tune the audio for the best detection performance.

0:02:43.535 --> 0:02:49.567
After re-running the analysis with the filters applied, we can see that two Spotted Crake calls were detected this time.

0:03:10.463 --> 0:03:15.462
After saving records, they can be explored whenever you come back to the application, and you will find them under the Records menu.

0:03:27.226 --> 0:03:33.225
Nocmig mode suppresses daylight records, so disable it to see them

0:03:44.089 --> 0:03:47.089
alongside any previously saved records...

0:03:49.088 --> 0:03:51.726
Thanks for watching!
